Looking at this proof goal, I need to show that for all but finitely many `v`, a certain bijection property holds. This is about showing that `φᵥ` (the base change of `φ` to the `v`-adic completion) restricts to an automorphism of the integral lattice for all but finitely many `v`.

The key insight is that for a linear automorphism `φ : V ≃ₗ[ℚ] V` of a ℚ-vector space, when we tensor with the `v`-adic completions, the resulting map preserves the image of the integral lattice for all but finitely many primes `v`. This is because `φ` comes from a global automorphism and integral lattices behave well under base change for almost all primes.

The bijection we need follows from the fact that `continuousBaseChange` is a continuous linear equivalence, and equivalences preserve bijections on subsets. Since `φ` is defined over ℚ and the integral lattice is defined over ℤ, for almost all `v`, the map will preserve integrality.

